                <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/331: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-12T09:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 12, 1932—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>103. Embassy learns authentic source <persName corresp="#p_TMGRL1"
                        >Trujillo</persName> only partially occupied by Government July 11, 4 p.m.
                    and street fighting and sniping continued. Total casualties exceed 100.</p>
                <p>Only Americans thought to be the city are <persName corresp="#p_JHA1">H. A.
                        Jaynes</persName>, United States Department of Agriculture, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_EA1">Arthur Erickson</persName>, Pentecostal missionary.</p>
                <p>Situation in Lima normal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Burdett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
